com.ltsllc.miranda.clientinterface.basicclasses

Class Event

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.ltsllc.miranda.clientinterface.basicclasses.Mergeable
      • com.ltsllc.miranda.clientinterface.basicclasses.MirandaObject
        • com.ltsllc.miranda.clientinterface.basicclasses.Event
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    DirectoryEntry, Equivalent, Evictable

    public class Event
extends MirandaObject
implements DirectoryEntry, Evictable
    An HTTP POST/PUT/DELETE that has been made to a topic.

    Properties

    Name Type Description
    guid String A string that identifies an Event from all the other events in the system.
    method enum, Methods The HTTP verb used for this instance. Currently this is one of POST PUT or DELETE
    userName String The name of the User who created this Event.
    timeOfCreation long The time returned by System.currentTimeMillis() when the Event was created.
    topicName String The name of the Topic that this instance was published to.
    awaitingDelivery List of Objects

    The objects that are trying to deliver the Event.

    Generally, clients do not interact with this property directly. Instead, clients use methods like addAwaitingDelivery(Object)} or canBeEvicted() to ascertain the state of this property.

    If this is empty, then it is because the Event has just been created or when everyone who was trying to deliver the Event has done so.

    content byte[]

    The content of an Event.

    The content of an Event is treated as a binary object even when the content is text --- Miranda can't tell the difference.

    This property can be null. This is generally the case for HTTP DELETE operations.

    In situations that an Event COULD have a content but does not, for example an HTTP POST that has an empty body, this property will generally be a zero length array.

        public boolean isEquivalentTo(java.lang.Object o)
        Description copied from interface: Equivalent
        Return true if the receiver refers to the same thing as the argument.

        Two instances are equivalent if

        • The have the same class
        • Their "primary keys" are the same

        For example, if two users have the same user name, they are equivalent, but if the user has changed their email address then equals will return false.

        Specified by:
        isEquivalentTo in interface Equivalent
        Parameters:
        o - The other instance to compare against.
        Returns:
        True if the other instance is equivalent to the receiver, false otherwise.
